(47, 1, '2014-01-21 17:31:26', '2014-01-21 17:31:26', '<!--:en-->\r\n<h1>SUSTAIN - Support Urban Slum Children to Access Inclusive Non-formal education</h1>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Location of activities:</strong> Bangladesh- Dhaka City Corporation: 17 wards; and Chittagong City Corporation: 15 wards\r\n\r\n<strong>Project budget:</strong> 5,272,439\r\n\r\n<strong>EC contribution:</strong> 5,009,767\r\n\r\nI<strong>mplementing agency:</strong> Save the Children - Denmark\r\n\r\n<strong>Co-financing / Local partner</strong>: Organization for Women\'s Development in Bangladesh (OWDEB); Social &amp; Economic Enhancement Programme (SEEP); Nari Maitree Association (NM); Society for Underprivileged Families (SUF); and Underprivileged Children’s Educational Programmes (UCEP)\r\n\r\n<strong>Starting date of implementation (contract signature date):</strong> 02 December 2011\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected end date:</strong> 01 December 2017\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Overall Objectives:</strong>\r\n\r\nTo increase equal access to quality basic education in a safe learning environment for hardest to reach children in urban slums of Dhaka and Chittagong and mainstream students into the formal education system or into other educational alternatives.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Project purpose:</strong>\r\n\r\nIncreased access to and completion of child-friendly pre-primary (PPE) and non-formal primary education (NFPE) has been achieved for hardest to reach urban working children or those at risk of becoming working children and create opportunities for continuing their formal or non-formal education beyond the provision of basic education.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Results:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 1:</strong> By end of project at least 8,000 children at risk of becoming working children have successfully completed 1-year Pre-primary education (PPE) and 30,888 out of school working children in the project area will complete condensed NFPE course.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 2:</strong> An English-based NFPE curriculum has been successfully introduced and tested in 3 NFPE centres.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 3:</strong> 20 thousand of the enrolled pre-primary and NFPE students have received parenting education and are actively supporting the education of the children.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 4:</strong> At least 13,406 NFPE completers/students are enrolled in formal schools to continue their education and students who cannot enrol into formal schools, are linked to alternative education opportunities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 5:</strong> Access to education for hardest to reach children in the project areas has been improved through child-led advocacy at local and national level.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 6:</strong> Government of Bangladesh is actively engaged in a dialogue to review the competency needs of hardest to reach children participating in the grade 5 final examinations.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 7: </strong>Participatory monitoring system on NFPE quality is in place and applied by the CMC members in the project area.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Present Status:</h2>\r\n<strong>Activities:</strong>\r\n\r\nSUSTAIN provides education for all types of working/slum children regardless of their socio-economic conditions, children with disabilities, indigenous and cultural minority groups etc. The Project established 39 rented compounds and enrolled 31,462 students against the target of 30,888 in their NFPE course.  It is estimated that at completion, SUSTAIN will produce nearly 30,000 primary school graduates (PECE passed). Another 8100 pupils will have been mainstreamed into government primary schools (GPS) at grade 1 having completed one-year pre-primary education (PPE) at SUSTAIN schools. There may not be any remaining pupil in any of the 39 project compounds at project closure.\r\n\r\nEnglish version of the government primary curriculum is piloted in 2 NFPE centres and comparative data between pilot and control centres showed higher English competency for students who were taught English through this approach. In 2016 a 3-day refresher training on the English curriculum for 10 NFPE teachers and 18 selected teachers from GPS were conducted in collaboration with Department of Primary Education (DPE) under the Ministry of Primary and Mass Education (MOPME)..\r\n\r\nParents of slum children usually value children’s work and income over their education. However, through parenting education sessions that focused on the importance of education for children, child development, child protection, child rights and relevant policies have had positive impact on the attitude and actions of more than 20 thousand parents and 3 thousand employers to support children’s education and development under the project.\r\n\r\nSUSTAIN follows a mainstream sensitization strategy for education, which involves networking with formal school teachers and provide after school tutorial support and teacher-student sensitization in the formal schooling system. So far 36 thousand formal school students, 136 formal school management committee (SMC) and 1,737 teachers have been sensitized. Around 83 percent students of SUSTAIN were enrolled in grade 6 of secondary schools after completing PECE. Among them around 5 percent PECE graduates were enrolled in Technical and Vocational Education and Training Institutes (TVET) through the efforts of SUSTAIN.\r\n\r\nChild led advocacy is a key strategy that SUSTAIN uses in project areas for enhanced enrolment of students in the formal schools by reducing the hidden costs of education in public schools. A joint research was done by SUSTAIN and SHARE TA with the help of a local Consultant titled- “Hidden Causes and Costs that Hinder the Access of Working Children to Primary Education in Bangladesh.” SUSTAIN planned a national conference to disseminate the findings of the study.\r\n\r\nSo far there is no significant development on the reassessment of the competency for the grade 5 final examination (PECE)  reflecting the needs of hardest to reach children. However, SUSTAIN continues to keep the dialogue with relevant authorities.\r\n\r\nSUSTAIN has introduced a participatory monitoring and evaluation system using two kinds of tools - Quality Learning Environment (QLE) and Monitoring, Evaluation, Accountability and Learning (MEAL). At the community level parent and school management committee provide their feedback through mood meter, parents-teachers meeting, addressing concerns received through information box and employers school visits and sharing. At partners level it is done through conducting M&amp;E visit, MIS, staff meeting, knowledge sharing meeting with formal school, half yearly and annual review workshop. At central level its done through project management steering committee (PMSC) meetings.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Lessons Learned:</strong>\r\n\r\nEducation for the urban working children can be successfully organized when the local community, the parents, the children and their employers collaborate with each other and accept the value of education. However, during implementation the project faced difficulties in managing the rental and maintenance costs of school compounds due to devaluation of the EURO against local currency made worse by rising inflation of the local economy. Being located in urban slums the rental of the privately owned compounds is pretty high. This together with the salary costs of 3-5 teachers make the overall costs of a 5-room school compound unsustainable without continued donor or government funding.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>Updated:</strong> August 2017</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->SUSTAIN<!--:--><!--:bn-->সাস্তাইন<!--:-->', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sustain', '', '', '2017-09-13 02:59:55', '2017-09-13 02:59:55', '', 40, 'http://localhost/shareeducation/?page_id=47', 0, 'page', '', 0);
