(93, 1, '2014-01-21 20:06:58', '2014-01-21 20:06:58', '<!--:en--><h1 style=\"font-weight:bold; color:blue;\">First Cross Field Visit</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>The cross field visit was undertaken as an aspect of the work of the SHARE programme, supported by EUD. The programme instigates cross visits to the field work of the NGO programmes participating in SHARE, and was organization by SHARE Component II in conjunction with Dhaka Ahsania Mission (DAM). The programme was attended by two members of the Save the Children (Bangladesh) SUSTAIN programme and two members of the Alorgah (Lighthouse) programme of Caritas, with personnel from SHARE Component II and DAM. The full list of participants is recorded in Annex Two of this report.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The party visited to three communities, in relatively inaccessible parts of the Chittagong Hill Tracts region. As an aspect of their UNIQUE II programme, DAM has set Community Learning Centres (CLC) to provide primary education to children in remote areas, who because of distance and/or language have little opportunity to attend and succeed in formal primary education settings. The CLCs offer a four year primary programme with school hours agree with the local community. </p>\r\n\r\nThe plan for the visit is to be found in Annex One. The party stayed in Rangamati and travelled to some remote villages. These villages were \r\n•	Dokhaiya Parishad\r\n•	Kolabunia in Sapchori Parishad\r\n•	Debchori in Kapatai Parishad, \r\n\r\n<p>The communities are largely Chakma speaking. The party visited three Community Learning Centres (CLC), spent time in the classrooms and speaking with teachers, supervisors, CLC members, members of the other management groups. The villages are remote, needing both boat and car to reach them. DAM emphasized the point that these are by no means the most remote villages they work with. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this report I pull together the findings presented by the participants of the trip, and raised in discussion, a round table meeting and written reports. As many were very detailed and insightful, I quote some verbatim.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1 style=\"font-weight:bold; color:blue;\">Purposes of the cross field visit</h1>\r\n•	For SHARE partner NGOs to get to know each other’s work;\r\n•	For SHARE NGOs to gain benefit from information sharing and networking;\r\n•	To provide a forum for learning by contrasting and comparing differing modes of working.\r\n\r\n<h1 style=\"font-weight:bold; color:blue;\">Objectives of the cross field visit</h1>\r\n•	to see one SHARE partner’s programme in action;\r\n•	to jointly analyse questions raised by the visits, in particular, those identified by individual partner NGOs;\r\n•	to begin to identify areas which could benefit from action research.\r\n\r\n<h1 style=\"font-weight:bold; color:blue;\">Participants’ objectives</h1>\r\nBefore the trip, in order to promote detailed observations and an enquiring attitude, the participants were asked to reflect on their own objectives for the trip. The procedure also allowed the trip to be honed to the needs and expectations of the participants.\r\n\r\nThe expectations were remarkable uniform.  Participants indicated their interest in:\r\n•	criteria for the selection location of the schools/centres\r\n•	teacher’s delivery and classroom organization for multigrade classrooms with school improvement processes\r\n•	the field supervisors’ monitoring process\r\n•	reporting systems\r\n•	health procedures\r\n•	promotion of mother tongue in early learning\r\nIt became clear that the participants wanted to investigate UNIQUE II’s management procedures as we as practice and in response to this DAM. arranged for their operatives to travel to the selected CLCs with us, allowing questions to be asked in the field. They also provided a round \r\n\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.sajibbiswas.com/shareeducation/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/First-Cross-Field-Visit.docx\" class=\"more\" >Download File</a><!--:--><!--:bn-->ক্রস ক্ষেত্রের ভিজিট ক্