(302, 1, '2017-09-13 03:15:34', '2017-09-13 03:15:34', '<h1><!--:en-->Technical Assistance</h1>\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Location of activities:</strong> Bangladesh\n\n<strong>EC contribution:</strong> 2,752600\n\n<strong>Implementing agency:</strong> Hulla and Co. Human Dynamics KG, Austria\n\n<strong>Co-financing / Local partner:</strong> The Centre for British Teachers (CfBT Education Trust), UK; The Institute of Governance Studies (IGS), BRAC, Bangladesh; and CARE Osterreich, Austria\n\n<strong>Starting date of implementation (contract signature date):</strong> 25 January 2012\n\n<strong>Expected end date:</strong> 24 July 2018\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Overall Objectives:</strong>\n\nTo contribute to the achievement of Bangladesh’s development goals and to a national basic education framework.\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n<strong>Project Purpose:</strong>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To share and disseminate lessons learned, best practices and quality materials so that they                are used in the NGO community and, if desired by responsible government agencies.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Results:</strong>\n\n<strong>Expected Result 1:</strong> Lessons learned, best practices and materials shared and disseminated, and used in the NGO community and, if desired by government, responsible government agencies to inform policy and practices (result 3 of the SHARE education programme)\n\n<strong>Expected Result 2:</strong> Results-based management institutionalized at NGOs and, if desired by government, at relevant government institutions (result 4 of the SHARE education programme).\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Present Status:</strong>\n\nThe Technical Assistance Component of SHARE programme is a discrete component on knowledge management, capacity building and coordination &amp; networking within the overall parameters of SHARE education programme and is designed specifically to yield lessons about what works best and why, share best practices, and help build results-based-management capacity and culture, as well as facilitating coherent linkages with the formal primary education system and other Non-formal Education (NFE) initiatives.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nDespite the slow progress in the first two years the TA has been repositioned on a more strategic platform in 2014 with a view to maximize the added value to the implementing project partners and the ultimate beneficiaries. Conceptual issues regarding the role and responsibilities of the TA project within the broader framework of SHARE were clarified and all key stakeholders of SHARE projects have been engaged in interactive roles through frequent meetings of the SHARE Coordination Group (SCG) and regular consultations with EUD. Meaningful networking with GOB agencies is established, and the potential benefits of SHARE programme to the larger NGO community has been recognized. Policy and action research in NFPE have been initiated, and upgraded EMIS and website have been established.\n\nIn order to strengthen the capacity of result-based management via monitoring and evaluation a M&amp;E Toolkit was prepared and disseminated through a participating process where all project personnel, consultant and the TA team were involved in a highly collaborative manner.\n\nThe TA team published and distributed three comprehensive SHARE Annual Reports since 2014 and organized four Annual Conferences which were considered huge success in terms of wider participation, quality of discussions and high relevance of the themes selected. These are all documented and shared with stakeholders.\n\nFollowing the 3<sup>rd</sup> annual conference held in June 2015 a community based schooling quality improvement Initiative (CBSQ-I) was established as an alliance of about 20 like-minded NGOs. CBSQ-I conducted series of activities through which a common quality framework for basic education together with a set of minimum service standards was established. This will serve as a benchmark of quality in NGO schools.\n\nA key task of the TA is to capture, support and document the innovations and good practices developed and implemented by the partner NGOs and to reflect and learn from each other’s experience. This is being achieved through cross field visits of NGO projects; advocacy and networking between GO and NGOs; and upstream research activities and sharing of the research outcomes.\n\nAccordingly, six cross field visits were conducted in various parts of the country. Each one was participated by SHARE and Non-SHARE NGOs including BRAC, NETZ, Educo, GSS, Plan International and CAMPE. The cross-field visits enabled participants to see field level practice of other than their own, which has relevance to their work and from which they will gained new knowledge and reflective skills. External networking is established among the participating NGOs and between the NGOs and government agencies both at central and local levels\n\nTo date, Seven monographs were printed and widely distributed as knowledge products. These are: 1<em>) Innovations and Excellence in Basic Education: Evidence from International Experience; 2) Innovations and Good Practice in SHARE Education Programme; 3) Innovations and Good Practices of NGO Schools-Lessons from SHARE Third Annual Conference; 4) Mother Tongue-based Multilingual Education: Lessons Learned in SHARE Education Programme; 5) Non-Formal Primary Education: A Subsector Policy and Strategy Study; 6) Competency-based Assessment in Primary Education in Bangladesh-A Review; and 7) Hidden Causes and Costs that Hinder the Access of Working Children to Primary Education</em>.\n\nTwelve Knowledge Sharing Seminars were held for disseminating the findings of the above research studies.\n\nFive newspaper articles written by the Team Leader were published in English language dailies including the Daily Star, Dhaka Tribune and the Independent on contributions of EU funded SHARE Education Programme and lessons learned in the context of Bangladesh’s development agenda.\n\n<strong>EU’s visibility</strong> received significant boost as a result of the activities of SHARE TA through print and electronic news, newspaper articles, SHARE Facebook page, and website. As of 5 April SHARE website was visited by 85,074 visitors.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Lessons Learned:</strong>\n\nThe concept and design of the associated TA to support the overall SHARE Education Programme is innovative and highly relevant to its context. However, as the MTR Report noted had the TA been given management oversight functions, the implementation of the four discrete projects under the programme would have been more coherent and efficient. In future design of technical assistance project this lesson may be considered.\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->Technical Assistance<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '162-autosave-v1', '', '', '2017-09-13 03:15:34', '2017-09-13 03:15:34', '', 162, 'http://www.sajibbiswas.com/shareeducation/162-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(303, 1, '2014-02-02 18:26:21', '2014-02-02 18:26:21', '<!--:en--><strong><h1>TA</h1></strong>\r\nThe mid-term review of SHARE\'s predecessor NFPE programme highlighted that the exchange of information and best practice among the NGOs in the network as well as with the government and other civil society actors is an important ingredient of success. Knowledge management, capacity building and coordination have consequently been scaled up and streamlined; and they have become the core of one of the two components of the SHARE programme. Thus, Technical Assistance (TA) is concerned with knowledge management, capacity building, coordination, policy dialogue and synthesis of lessons learned. As a discrete component located within the overall SHARE programme TA is specifically designed to yield lessons about what works best and why, to share best practice, and to help build results-based-management capacity and culture, in coherent linkages with the formal primary education system and other NFE initiatives. TA has a duration of 78 months, starting on Jan 25th 2012 and ending on 24th July 2018.\r\nThe overall objective for SHARE TA component is the same as that of four SHARE projects, that is: to contribute to the achievement of Bangladesh’s development goals and to a national basic education framework.\r\n<strong><h3>The TA of the SHARE programme has four main thrusts:</h3></strong>\r\n1.	sharing experience among SHARE partner NGOs, with the NGO community at large and with Government;\r\n2.	extending and disseminating information produced by SHARE;\r\n3.	supporting the development of current practice in education;\r\n4.	supporting NGOs to improve their effectiveness, further define their roles and to forge stronger links with Government.\r\n5.	A particular work of component II is setting up of an interactive web site. It will be in action by the end of the first year of implementation and will host documents created through the project and the programme’s database.\r\nTA addresses Results Three and Four of the SHARE education programme.\r\n<strong><h3>Result Three is:</h3></strong>\r\nlessons learned, best practices and materials shared and disseminated, and used in the NGO community and, if desired by government, responsible government agencies to inform policy and practice.\r\n<strong><h3>Result Four is:</h3></strong>\r\nresults-based management institutionalised by NGOs and, if desired by government, at relevant government institutions.\r\nThis Component is implementing by a consortium led by Human Dynamics, Austria. Consortium members are Centre for British Teachers (CfBT Education Trust), UK; The Institute of Governance Studies (IGS), BRAC, Bangladesh; and CARE Osterreich, Austria.\r\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->TA<!--:--><!--:bn-->TA<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '162-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-02 18:26:21', '2014-02-02 18:26:21', '', 162, 'http://www.sajibbiswas.com/shareeducation/162-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(304, 1, '2014-02-02 18:27:37', '2014-02-02 18:27:37', '<!--:en--><h1>SUSTAIN - Support Urban Slum Children to Access Inclusive Non-formal education</h1>\r\n<strong><h3>Objectives</h3></strong>\r\nOverall Objective: To increase equal access to quality basic education in a safe learning environment for hardest to reach children in urban slums of Dhaka and Chittagong and mainstream students into the formal education system or into other educational alternatives.\r\n<strong>Specific Objective 1:</strong> Increased access to and completion of child-friendly pre-primary (PPE) and non-formal primary education (NFPE) has been achieved for hardest to reach urban working children or those at risk of becoming working children.\r\n<strong>Specific Objective 2:</strong> Increased opportunities for the hardest to reach working children or those at risk of becoming working children in urban areas for continuing their formal or non-formal education beyond the provision of basic education.\r\n<strong>Specific Objective 3:</strong> Improved inclusiveness and quality of the primary education provision.\r\n<strong><h3>Key Results</h3></strong>\r\n1.	8,000 children at risk have successfully completed1-year PPE<br/>\r\n2.	30,888 out of school working children condensed NFPE course\r\n3.	English-based NFPE curriculum has been successfully introduced\r\n4.	20,000 guardians have received parenting education\r\n5.	13,406 are enrolled in formal schools to continue their education\r\n6.	Children who cannot enroll into formal schools, are linked to alternative education opportunities\r\n7.	Access to education for hardest to reach children improved through child-led advocacy\r\n8.	GoB is actively engaged in a dialogue to review the competency needs\r\n9.	Participatory monitoring system on NFPE quality is in place and applied by the CMC members in the project area.\r\n<strong><h3>Target Groups</h3></strong>\r\n1.	38,988 urban working children\r\n2.	17,500 parents and 2,500 employers of the children,\r\n3.	76,800 formal school students,\r\n4.	192 SMCs and 960 teachers from formal schools,\r\n5.	400 local government/ward officials,\r\n6.	50 state officials from MOPME and NCTB\r\n7.	250 representatives from primary education and NFPE providing organizations/institutions\r\n<strong><h3>Contract</h3></strong>\r\nRef. DCI-ASIE/2011/262-810\r\n<h3>Duration</h3>\r\nDecember 2011 – December 2017\r\n<strong><h3>Location</h3></strong>\r\nDhaka City Corporation: 17 wards \r\nChittagong City Corporation: 15 wards\r\n<strong><h3>Budget</h3></strong>\r\nTotal budget: EURO 5,273,439\r\nCurrent year budget: EURO 951,208\r\n<strong><h3>Contributions</h3></strong>\r\nEU: EURO 5,009,767 (95%)\r\nSC: EURO 263,672 (5%)\r\n<strong><h3>Partners</h3></strong>\r\nNari Maitree (NM)\r\nSociety for Underprivileged Families (SUF)\r\nSocial and Economic Enhancement Program (SEEP)\r\nUnderprivileged Children’s Educational Program (UCEP)\r\nOrganization for Women Development in Bangladesh (OWDEB)\r\n<strong><h3>Project Design</h3></strong>\r\n1.	The project activities take place in physical structures based on a compound system.\r\n2.	To cover all targeted 30888 NFPE students, 39 compound building will be rented.\r\n3.	Within 39 compounds, 27 will include 1 PPE centre each to cover the targeted 8100 PPE students.\r\n4.	Each of the 39 compounds will cover 4 NFPE centers and 1 child club.\r\n5.	Each PPE, NFPE centre and child club will have 1 room within the compounds.\r\n6.	PPE centers each room will accommodate two (2) classes/shifts with 25 students each.\r\n7.	NFPE centers each room will accommodate three (3) classes/shifts with 30 students each.\r\n8.	In project areas where the necessary building infrastructure is not available, a catchment area of around two square kilometers in average is considered to accommodate the compounds. The setup will ensure short distance for the PPE and NFPE students to attend the centers and co-curricular activities in the child clubs and it reduces the number of child clubs and CMCs needed, which contributes to a cost efficient project setup.\r\n9.	The description refers to 39 compounds/catchment areas, with 156 NFPE centers (4 centers per compound/catchment areax39) and 27 PPE centers and 39 child clubs and 39 CMCs.\r\n<strong><h3>Main Activities</h3></strong>\r\n1.	Provision of PPE and NFPE\r\n2.	Piloting of English based NFPE curriculum\r\n3.	Child clubs\r\n4.	Parenting education for guardians\r\n5.	Sensitisation of stakeholders on constraints of working children\r\n6.	Tutorial support for graduated students to access formal school system\r\n7.	Local level child-led advocacy\r\n8.	Advocacy with GoB to review the requirements for grade 5 examinations\r\n9.	Development of a comprehensive monitoring guideline for learning centres\r\n10.	Documentation of best practices\r\n<strong><h3>Progress ( January to May  2012)</h3></strong>\r\n1.	Staff recruitment: Staff recruitment of both Save the Children (SC) and 5 partners has been completed by this time. Total staff recruited 388.\r\n2.	Student Survey: Student survey for enrollment of PPE and NFE has been completed.\r\n3.	Student Enrollment: 1350 PPE and 14040 NFPE students enrolled.\r\n4.	Set up Compound: All 39 compounds including 1 PPE, 4 NFPE and 1 Child Club have been established.\r\n5.	Communication and Visibility plan: The communication and Visibility plan has been approved by EU.\r\n6.	Steering Committee (PMSC): Project steering committee has been formed. ToR for the steering committee has been finalized.\r\n7.	Procurement of Centre Logistics: All school materials for 39 compounds have been procured.\r\n8.	Procurement of Education Materials: All learning materials for 1350 PPE students and 14040 NFPE students have been procured.\r\n9.	Basic Training for PPE and NFPE teachers: 9 batches of Basic training for PPE and NFPE teachers have been completed.\r\n10.	Provision of Information Box: All 183 centers established information box.\r\n11.	Baseline Survey: Baseline survey for SUSTAIN project is going on in 38 wards.\r\n<strong><h3>Next Highlights Activities (June to August 2012)</h3></strong>\r\n1.	Completion of Baseline Survey in 38 wards of Dhaka and Chittagong City Corporation.\r\n2.	Publication of Communication, Visibility and Behavioral Change and Communication (BCC) materials and distribute to relevant stakeholders.\r\n3.	Organize workshop on Review and Condensing of English Curriculum.\r\n4.	Organize Basic Training for NFPE and Selected formal School teachers on English curriculum.\r\n5.	Organize Basic Training for Community Mobilizers on Parenting Education.\r\n6.	Organize Basic Training for Child Club Facilitators on child-led advocacy and life skills.\r\n7.	Initiate co-curricular activities through Child Club.\r\n<h3>Contact</h3>\r\n<strong>Name:</strong>Shahida Begum\r\n<strong>Position:</strong>Program Director-EYE\r\n<strong>Email:</strong> shahida.begum@savethechildren.org\r\n<strong>Address:</strong>House No. CWN (A) 35, Road No. 43\r\nGulshan-2, Dhaka 1212\r\n<strong>Tell:</strong> +88029861690\r\n<strong>Cell: </strong>01713279587\r\n\r\n<!--:--><!--:bn-->প্রথম ওয়ানডেতে শতক করা অ্যারন ফিঞ্চ শুক্রবার কোনো রান করতে পারেননি, ক্রিস জর্ডানের বলে এক্সট্রা কাভারে গ্যারি ব্যালান্সকে ক্যাচ দিয়েছেন। অন্য উদ্বোধনী ব্যাটসম্যান ডেভিড ওয়ার্নার জর্ডানকেই ফিরতি ক্যাচ দিলে ২ উইকেটে ৩২ রানে পরিণত হয় অস্ট্রেলিয়া। প্রথম ওয়ানডেতে শতক করা অ্যারন ফিঞ্চ শুক্রবার কোনো রান করতে পারেননি, ক্রিস জর্ডানের বলে এক্সট্রা কাভারে গ্যারি ব্যালান্সকে ক্যাচ দিয়েছেন। অন্য উদ্বোধনী ব্যাটসম্যান ডেভিড ওয়ার্নার জর্ডানকেই ফিরতি ক্যাচ দিলে ২ উইকেটে ৩২ রানে পরিণত হয় অস্ট্রেলিয়া।প্রথম ওয়ানডেতে\r\n\r\nপ্রথম ওয়ানডেতে শতক করা অ্যারন ফিঞ্চ শুক্রবার কোনো রান করতে পারেননি, ক্রিস জর্ডানের বলে এক্সট্রা কাভারে গ্যারি ব্যালান্সকে ক্যাচ দিয়েছেন। অন্য উদ্বোধনী ব্যাটসম্যান ডেভিড ওয়ার্নার জর্ডানকেই ফিরতি ক্যাচ দিলে ২ উইকেটে ৩২ রানে পরিণত হয় অস্ট্রেলিয়া। প্রথম ওয়ানডেতে শতক করা অ্যারন ফিঞ্চ শুক্রবার কোনো রান করতে পারেননি, ক্রিস জর্ডানের বলে এক্সট্রা কাভারে গ্যারি ব্যালান্