ren\r\n5. Build capacity of network bodies and action groups\r\n6. Arrange accommodation, food and education materials for geographically excluded children\r\n7. Identify and arrange facilities for children with special needs\r\n8. Develop and provide learning materials, Multilingual Education (MLE) and Information, Education and Communication (IEC) materials\r\n9. Raise awareness and life-skills development activities for parents and guardians\r\n10. Develop advocacy strategy and undertake advocacy programs.\r\n11. Geographical Coverage: A total of 1,005 villages in 104 upazila (sub-district) under 27 districts of Chittagong, Rangpur, Khulna, Dhaka, Rajshahi and Sylhet divisions of Bangladesh.\r\n<h3>Project Cost:</h3>\r\nThe total project cost is EURO 10,458,658.90. Out of that EURO 9,935700 (95%) from the European Union and EURO 522,958.9 (5%) from Secours Catholique - Caritas France.\r\nStaff Strength: Project staff- 159 and Teachers- 1,339\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->Aloghar<!--:--><!--:bn-->আলোঘর<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '42-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-18 02:44:53', '2015-06-18 02:44:53', '', 42, 'http://share-education.org/42-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(679, 1, '2015-06-18 02:50:06', '2015-06-18 02:50:06', '<!--:en--><h1>SUSTAIN - Support Urban Slum Children to Access Inclusive Non-formal education</h1>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<h3>Objectives</h3>\r\n<strong>Overall Objective</strong>: To increase equal access to quality basic education in a safe learning environment for hardest to reach children in urban slums of Dhaka and Chittagong and mainstream students into the formal education system or into other educational alternatives.\r\n\r\n<strong>Specific Objective 1:</strong> Increased access to and completion of child-friendly pre-primary (PPE) and non-formal primary education (NFPE) has been achieved for hardest to reach urban working children or those at risk of becoming working children.\r\n<strong>Specific Objective 2:</strong> Increased opportunities for the hardest to reach working children or those at risk of becoming working children in urban areas for continuing their formal or non-formal education beyond the provision of basic education.\r\n<strong>Specific Objective 3:</strong> Improved inclusiveness and quality of the primary education provision.\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Key Results</h3>\r\n1. 8,000 children at risk have successfully completed1-year PPE\r\n2. 30,888 out of school working children condensed NFPE course\r\n3. English-based NFPE curriculum has been successfully introduced\r\n4. 20,000 guardians have received parenting education\r\n5. 13,406 are enrolled in formal schools to continue their education\r\n6. Children who cannot enroll into formal schools, are linked to alternative education opportunities\r\n7. Access to education for hardest to reach children improved through child-led advocacy\r\n8. GoB is actively engaged in a dialogue to review the competency needs\r\n9. Participatory monitoring system on NFPE quality is in place and applied by the CMC members in the project area.\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Target Groups</h3>\r\n1. 38,988 urban working children\r\n2. 17,500 parents and 2,500 employers of the children,\r\n3. 76,800 formal school students,\r\n4. 192 SMCs and 960 teachers from formal schools,\r\n5. 400 local government/ward officials,\r\n6. 50 state officials from MOPME and NCTB\r\n7. 250 representatives from primary education and NFPE providing organizations/institutions\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Duration</h3>\r\nDecember 2011 – December 2017\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Operational Area</h3>\r\nDhaka City Corporation: 17 wards\r\nChittagong City Corporation: 15 wards\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Budget</h3>\r\nTotal budget: EURO 5,273,439\r\nCurrent year budget: EURO 951,208\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Contributions</h3>\r\nEU: EURO 5,009,767 (95%)\r\nSC: EURO 263,672 (5%)\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Partners</h3>\r\n1. Nari Maitree (NM)\r\n2. Society for Underprivileged Families (SUF)\r\n3. Social and Economic Enhancement Program (SEEP)\r\n4. Underprivileged Children’s Educational Program (UCEP)\r\n5. Organization for Women Development in Bangladesh (OWDEB)\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Project Design</h3>\r\n1. The project activities take place in physical structures based on a compound system.\r\n2. To cover all targeted 30888 NFPE students, 39 compound building will be rented.\r\n3. Within 39 compounds, 27 will include 1 PPE centre each to cover the targeted 8100 PPE students.\r\n4. Each of the 39 compounds will cover 4 NFPE centers and 1 child club.\r\n5. Each PPE, NFPE centre and child club will have 1 room within the compounds.\r\n6. PPE centers each room will accommodate two (2) classes/shifts with 25 students each.\r\n7. NFPE centers each room will accommodate three (3) classes/shifts with 30 students each.\r\n8. In project areas where the necessary building infrastructure is not available, a catchment area of around two square kilometers in average is considered to accommodate the compounds. The setup will ensure short distance for the PPE and NFPE students to attend the centers and co-curricular activities in the child clubs and it reduces the number of child clubs and CMCs needed, which contributes to a cost efficient project setup.\r\n9. The description refers to 39 compounds/catchment areas, with 156 NFPE centers (4 centers per compound/catchment areax39) and 27 PPE centers and 39 child clubs and 39 CMCs.\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3>Main Activities</h3>\r\n1. Provision of PPE and NFPE\r\n2. Piloting of English based NFPE curriculum\r\n3. Child clubs\r\n4. Parenting education for guardians\r\n5. Sensitisation of stakeholders on constraints of working children\r\n6. Tutorial support for graduated students to access formal school system\r\n7. Local level child-led advocacy\r\n8. Advocacy with GoB to review the requirements for grade 5 examinations\r\n9. Development of a comprehensive monitoring guideline for learning centres\r\n10. Documentation of best practices\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\nContact<strong></strong>\r\n\r\nShahida Begum\r\n<strong></strong>Program Director-EYE\r\n<strong></strong>shahida.begum@savethechildren.org\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->SUSTAIN<!--:--><!--:bn-->সাস্তাইন<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '47-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-18 02:50:06', '2015-06-18 02:50:06', '', 47, 'http://share-education.org/47-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(680, 1, '2015-06-18 02:51:54', '2015-06-18 02:51:54', '<!--:en--><strong> </strong>\r\n<h3>UNIQUE (Unique intervention for quality primary education)-II</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>\r\n<strong>Introduction</strong>\r\nEducation is an important element in the struggle for human rights. It serves as a vital pathway out of poverty. In Bangladesh, however, many children remain excluded from education due to the complex nature of inequities. A substantial number of children still drop out of the schooling system or discontinue their education. The effect appears even stronger with respect to girl children. Though the number and proportion of out of school children has reduced over the years in Bangladesh, it still remains considerably high and needs the attention of educational planners and administrators.\r\nDhaka Ahsania Mission (DAM) is a leading non-government organisation in Bangladesh dedicated to improving the human condition of the disadvantaged people of the society. With its enduring growth over time, DAM has implemented a large number of projects covering different areas of development. Education always remains at the top of the DAM’s development agenda. Considering non-formal education as a means of integration into society, DAM has contributed significantly towards influencing change for prevailing non-formal education system in Bangladesh.\r\nUnique Intervention for Quality Primary Education-UNIQUE II is a 6-year project started its activities in December 2011. The project is being implemented with financial support of the European Union. The major objective of the project is to impart quality education to out-of-school and drop-out children particularly from the disadvantaged group through the opening of complete multigrade classes. It also intends to provide remedial services to the slow learners of targeted government and registered primary schools. UNIQUE-II aims at promoting, facilitating and managing greater community involvement and allowing the local community to participate at all stages of the project cycle. The project works for creating sufficient ownership of the local people with the aim of making more resilient and vibrant communities.\r\n<strong>Overall objective</strong>\r\nTo contribute to develop a collaborative basic education system that enables primary school aged children to avail quality education\r\n<strong>Specific objectives</strong>\r\n1. To provide primary and pre-primary education to 297,467 disadvantaged children from the targeted geographically susceptible upazilas\r\n2. To develop institutional collaboration and horizontal learning mechanism between formal and non-formal primary education providers\r\n3. To document and disseminate effective practices and lessons\r\n4. Key Expected Results\r\n5. Effectiveness of non-formal primary education programmes increased in 26 targeted districts through reaching the out-of-school children and catering for their learning needs\r\n6. Children’s performance improved in formal schools of targeted 84 upazilas\r\n7. Child-centred learning community and supportive environment developed in the targeted 454 unions of the project\r\n\r\n<strong>Project Partners</strong>\r\nThe project is being implemented by a consortium of partners with Dhaka Ahsania Mission (DAM) as the lead agency. The other implementing partners of the project include Assistance for Social Organization and Development (ASOD), Christian Commission for Development in Bangladesh (CCDB), Development Organisation of the Rural Poor (DORP), Padakhep Manabik Unnayan Kendra (PMUK), SUROVI, Voluntary Association for Rural Development (VARD) and Young Power in Social Action (YPSA). Besides, Plan Bangladesh supports the project as a technical partner.\r\n\r\n<strong>Project Implementation and Management</strong>\r\nThe UNIQUE-II project is being implemented through a decentralised management system to afford substantial autonomy at all levels of operation. The Central Team is supported through 8 Regional and 71 Area Offices. All Children Learning Centres (CLC) are managed by the community through CLC Management Committees (CMC). CLCs are usually multipurpose centres for the local community as a whole. Besides, a Learning Resource Centre (LRC) is operated and managed by the community people in each of the unions of the project area. LRCs offer a wide range of community managed programmes and services.\r\n\r\n<strong>Geographical Coverage</strong>\r\nBandarban, Bagherhat, Barguna, Barisal, Bhola, Dhaka, Dinajpur, Rangamati, Chittagong, Feni, Gaibandha, Gazipur, Jamalpur, Khagrachari, Kishorgonj, Kurigram, Lalmonirhat, Laxmipur, Mymensingh, Narayanganj, Netrokona, Nilphamari, Noakhali, Patuakhali, Rangpur, and Satkhira.\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->UNIQUE-II<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-18 02:51:54', '2015-06-18 02:51:54', '', 49, 'http://share-education.org/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
