(693, 1, '2015-06-22 09:37:38', '2015-06-22 09:37:38', '<!--:en--><strong> </strong>\r\n<h1>Aloghar (Lighthouse)</h1>\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Overview</strong></h3>\r\n<strong></strong>\r\nCaritas Bangladesh believes education is key to sustainable and human resource development. Therefore, this organization has been operating different projects over four decades in the arena of formal, non-formal and vocational education for the poor, hard to reach and underprivileged children including different indigenous communities, excluded and untouchable backgrounds.\r\nTo enhance contribution to national education framework by increasing literacy rate among the disadvantaged children and creating an opportunity for them to acquire skills and become efficient citizens, Caritas Bangladesh initiated six-year project titled \"Aloghar (Lighthouse) - Supporting the Hardest to Reach Through Basic Education (SHARE)\" in November 2011 with financial support of the European Union and Secours Catholique - Caritas France.\r\nAloghar mainly focuses on basic inclusive primary education through non-formal environment with arrangement of 1,005 education centers for the poverty stricken children who live in the most inaccessible areas including the indigenous communities and those with special needs. The project actions are designed to supplement government efforts to achieve development goal. The community teachers impart quality education to the disadvantaged children from early childhood to grade five through multi-grade approach using textbooks of National Curriculum and Textbook Board (NCTB) along with supplementary books and teaching aids in a joyful atmosphere. There is a provision for indigenous pupils to learn in their mother tongue side by side Bengali. This intervention is expected to equip the enrolled pupils with competencies and human qualities towards overall development and self-reliance.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Goal</strong><strong></strong></h3>\r\nIncreased empowerment, enhanced literacy, self-reliance and better social integration of the disadvantaged and hardest to reach children.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Specific Objective</strong><strong></strong></h3>\r\nThe hardest to reach children enjoy their right to quality basic education at pre and primary level, and equal opportunities for inclusion in mainstream education at secondary level.\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Expected Results</strong></h3>\r\n1. Disadvantaged communities have ready access to effectively functioning education centers conducive to learning environment.\r\n2. Indigenous children at pre and primary level have the opportunity to learn in their native languages in addition to Bengali\r\n3. Effective inclusive education is assured for the Children with Special Needs (CSN).\r\n4. Parents of the hardest to reach children are sensitized to family life-skills such as: literacy, numeracy, sanitation, hygiene, climate change, disaster risk management, etc.\r\n5. Effective advocacy mechanism is in place for educational mainstreaming of the hardest to reach communities through establishing a network which includes Community Based Organizations (CBOs), civil society and government agencies.\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Target Group</strong></h3>\r\nThe total number of direct beneficiaries of the project is 158,605 within the age of 5-14 years. Among the beneficiaries 100,000 children are out-of-school and 58,605 drop-outs. They are from indigenous and ethnic minority communities (90,000), the poorest families (61,605) and with special needs (7,000).\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<h3><strong>Major Activities</strong></h3>\r\n1. Develop baseline of family profiles for the intervention\r\n2. Establish/refurbish education centres\r\n3. Form multi-stakeholder networks, Education Centre Management Committee (EMC) and Action Groups for advocacy\r\n4. Link up with Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR) initiatives of private organizations to provide nutritious mid-day meals for the children\r\n5. Build capacity of network bodies and action groups\r\n6. Arrange accommodation, food and education materials for geographically excluded children\r\n7. Identify and arrange facilities for children with special needs\r\n8. Develop and provide learning materials, Multilingual Education (MLE) and Information, Education and Communication (IEC) materials\r\n9. Raise awareness and life-skills development activities for parents and guardians\r\n10. Develop advocacy strategy and undertake advocacy programs.\r\n11. Geographical Coverage: A total of 1,005 villages in 104 upazila (sub-district) under 27 districts of Chittagong, Rangpur, Khulna, Dhaka, Rajshahi and Sylhet divisions of Bangladesh.\r\n<h3><strong>Project Cost</strong></h3>\r\nThe total project cost is EURO 10,458,658.90. Out of that EURO 9,935700 (95%) from the European Union and EURO 522,958.9 (5%) from Secours Catholique - Caritas France.\r\n<strong>Staff Strength</strong>\r\n\r\nProject staff- 159 and Teachers- 1,339\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->Aloghar<!--:--><!--:bn-->আলোঘর<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '42-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-22 09:37:38', '2015-06-22 09:37:38', '', 42, 'http://share-education.org/42-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
