of the 27attainable competencies.\r\n\r\nBuilding on the success in SHIKHON’s first phase, and financed by the European Union, the SHIKHON Program has begun its second five-year phase, rolling out greater coverage across Bangladesh and additional activities. In addition to the NFPE model, SHIKHON will work in formal primary schools to support quality improvements that will result in equity in primary education for vulnerable children. In the second phase, SHIKHON will work in remote rural areas, riverine chars, (low lying flood and erosion prone areas) and haors (marshlands), hills, coastal areas and disaster prone areas in six of Bangladesh’s seven divisions. This program will be implemented by national NGOs who have long experience in education programming. Partnership with local communities is a key strength of SHIKHON schools and active participation of parents and school management committees (SMC) are vital to the success of SHIKHON schools.\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Global Objective</h3>\r\nTo contribute to the achievement of Bangladesh’s development goals, and to a national basic education framework.\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Specific Objective</h3>\r\nTo promote access and increase basic education outcomes for 160,400 of the hardest-to-reach and marginalized children, making use of lessons learned in SHIKHON’s first phase, while bringing about positive change in Bangladesh’ national education system.\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Target Groups</h3>\r\nOne hundred twenty-eight thousand four hundred (128,400) of the hardest-to-reach children from the poorest quintile of society living in remote disaster prone coastal areas, including chars and haors, the Chittagong Hill Tracts, and 32,000 low-performing, disadvantaged children attending formal schools in SHIKHON’s working areas. In addition, 102,720 parents of these hardest-to-reach children; 6,960 teachers and support teachers in SHIKHON schools, 47,000 local community members responsible for school management and 4,280 government education officials/teachers.\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Implementing Partners</h3>\r\n1. Community Development Centre (CODEC)\r\n2. RDRS Bangladesh (RDRS)\r\n3. Village Education Resource Centre (VERC)\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Results and major activities</h3>\r\nResult 1: Increased access to cost-effective non-formal basic education for hardest to reach children in targeted communities\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Major activities</h3>\r\n1. Participatory situation analysis to identify the status of primary education in targeted communities;\r\n2. Establish school readiness classes;\r\n3. Establish NFPE schools (from Grade I through Grade V);\r\n4. Establish SMCs in each school both to ensure that local communities participate in SHIKHON programming and to improve the capabilities of SMCs;\r\n5. In order to ensure quality education in formal primary school, establish early primary education (EPE) schools (pre-primary through Grade II) for children aged 5-7 years old in target communities so that they will be better prepared for formal education.\r\nResult 2: Increased efficiency and quality of non-formal basic education services using holistic approaches for children to succeed in school\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Major activities</h3>\r\n1. Develop and implement staff training to ensure and support quality primary education at all levels;\r\n2. Develop and publish class-wise and subject-based teaching and learning materials;\r\n3. Develop and operate class-wise and subject-based training courses for teachers;\r\n4. Develop an early primary education model and materials\r\n5. Develop multi-lingual education EPE model and materials\r\n6. Develop a monitoring and evaluation system;\r\n7. As part of Save the Children’s School Health and Nutrition Program, provide hand-washing facilities, conduct vision screening, supply vitamin-A, iron and de-worming tablets, and ensure access to safe drinking water and sanitation facilities in all SHIKHON schools;\r\n8. Establish children’s clubs to support low-performing children in formal schools.\r\nResult 3: Increased collaboration between the formal and non-formal primary sectors to promote sharing and adoption of best practices\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h3>Major activities</h3>\r\n1. Collect no objection certificate (NOC) from nearby formal primary school for every SHIKHON school;\r\n2. Facilitate the supervision of SHIKHON schools by government education officials;\r\n3. Provide support to formal schools for adopting active teaching and learning methodologies;\r\n4. Coordinate with government authorities to ensure that SHIKHON students sit the primary education completion exam;\r\n5. Secure permission for mainstreaming EPE students in Grade 3 in formal primary schools;\r\n6. Conduct research to improve primary education and support evidence based advocacy;\r\n7. Establish a network with primary education providers for creating a learning environment.\r\n\r\n<strong>Save the Children</strong>\r\n<strong>Bangladesh Country Office</strong>\r\n<strong>House No. CWN (A) 35, Road No. 43, Gulshan-2, Dhaka-1212</strong>\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div><!--:-->', '<!--:en-->SHIKHON-II<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '44-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-22 09:51:28', '2015-06-22 09:51:28', '', 44, 'http://share-education.org/44-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
