hildren because of their language and cultural differences.\r\n\r\nThere are a couple of important lessons to be learned from Aloghar Project experience. First, if children are taught in their mother language at very early stage it significantly enhances their participation and retention in schools. Secondly, the location of Aloghar schools seem to be carefully selected representing unserved or underserved areas, and the marginalized children most of whom are indigenous are well targeted. In addition, the backstopping of Aloghar schools by the churches enhanced their chances of success in the underprivileged community.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">updated: August 2017</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->Aloghar<!--:--><!--:bn-->আলোঘর<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '42-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-13 02:21:22', '2017-09-13 02:21:22', '', 42, 'http://share-education.org/42-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
