(940, 1, '2017-09-13 02:32:57', '2017-09-13 02:32:57', '<!--:en-->\r\n<h2>SHIKHON-II</h2>\r\n<strong>Location of activities:</strong> Bangladesh- 5 divisions, 17 districts and 58 Upazilas, 387 unions and 2582 villages of Bangladesh\r\n\r\n<strong>Project budget:</strong> 16,842,105 EURO\r\n\r\n<strong>EC contribution:</strong> 16,000,000\r\n\r\n<strong>Implementing agency:</strong> Save the Children – UK\r\n\r\n<strong>Co-financing / Local partner:</strong> Community Development Centre (CODEC); RDRS Bangladesh (RDRS); and Village Education Resource Centre (VERC)\r\n\r\n<strong>Starting date of implementation (contract signature date):</strong> 01 December 2011\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected end date:</strong> 30 November 2016 ( actual end date 28 February 2017)\r\n<h3>Description:</h3>\r\n<strong>Overall Objective (s):</strong>\r\n\r\nTo contribute to the achievement of Bangladesh’s development goals, and to a national basic education framework.\r\n\r\n<strong>Project purpose:</strong>\r\n\r\nTo promote access and increase basic education outcomes for 160,400 hardest to reach and marginalized children while catalysing lessons-learning and other positive change in Bangladesh’ national education system\r\n\r\n<strong>Results:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected </strong><strong>Result 1</strong>: <strong>Access</strong>- Increased access to cost-effective non-formal basic education for 128,400 hardest to reach children in targeted communities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 2</strong>: <strong>Quality</strong>- Increased efficiency and quality of non-formal basic education for 160,400 (128,400 non-formal+32,000 formal) children using holistic approaches for children to succeed in school.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 3</strong>:<strong> Linkages</strong>- Increased collaboration between the formal and non-formal primary education sectors to promote sharing and adoption of best practices.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Present Status:</h3>\r\n<strong>Activities:</strong>\r\n\r\nSHIKHON-II is the first among the 4 projects of SHARE education Programme to close in February 2017. All schools established by the project were closed in December 2016 as planned with students either completing their primary education cycle or mainstreamed into government primary schools (GPS).\r\n\r\nTo meet the expected result 1 relating to ‘Access’, SHIKHON-II established 4,290 schools in remote  coastal areas, chars and haors, and Chittagong Hill Tracts. Of this number 2,629 are Non-Formal Primary Education (NFPE) schools that offer readiness to grade 5 education and 1,661 Early Primary Education (EPE) schools that offer pre-primary to grade 2 education. SHIKHON-II enrolled 119,218 (69,181 NFPE &amp; 50,037 EPE) students including 569 adivasi/ethnic children through 30 Multi Lingual Education (MLE) centres in Chittagong Hill Tracts. The EPE students are mainstreamed to government primary schools (GPS) in the neighbouring areas at grade 3. A typical SHIKHON-II school is a community-provided, one-classroom school with one teacher who delivers education to a group of 30 to 35 children.\r\n\r\nIn total 68,439 students successfully passed the government’s primary education completion examination (PECE) and 47,872 pupils were mainstreamed into GPS at grade 3 having completed three-year education from pre-primary to grade 2 in SHIKHON-II schools.\r\n\r\nUnder the expected result 2 relating to ‘Quality’, the project ensured that the children acquire the necessary competencies at primary level. For this SHIKHON-II developed class-wise and subject-based teacher training courses and published class and subject specific teachers’ guides. SHIKHON-II teachers were trained in the SHIKHON accelerated curriculum, providing them with the experience and skills needed to help further their career. On average teachers received 3.4 month technical support visits by the teacher supervisor and technical officers. Parents and family members of SHIKHON students received parenting sessions on nutrition, early childhood development, and on how best they could support their children while they learn and develop. School Management Committees (SMCs) were established at every location and trained to oversee the operation of the school, as well as to develop and execute School Improvement Plans.\r\n\r\nTo address the expected result 3 relating to ‘Linkage’ SHIKHON-II developed  close relationship and networking with government agencies at central and field level. As a result all students of SHIKHON-II project schools received government support including clearence to operate schools, take the PECE exam, and free text books. The project established primary education change makers groups among GPS teachers who wanted to bring changesand improvements in their classroom teaching learning practices. The GPS teachers used phonetic charts of SHIKHON-II to upgrade  students’ pronunciation skills as well as teachers’ guidebooks produced by the project.\r\n\r\n<strong>Lessons Learned:</strong>\r\n\r\nSHIKHON-II completed its operation in two phases: first phase saw the closure of about 50% of schools and downsizing the staff to almost half, the later phase saw the closure of all remaining schools and termination of all staff. Both operations were carried out in planned way with least or no social problem. In various regions project closing ceremonies were held to recount the achievements and benefits of the project and to thank the local community for their support. The closing ceremonies were participated by the local communities, government officials and head masters of neighbouring government schools. SHIKHON-II successfully leveraged its strong relations with government officials to disseminate information about SHIKHON-II’s achievements while advocating for changes in government schools to make education more accessible to the marginalized. The experience of SHIKHON-II including lessons learned is being documented by Save the Children International.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>Updated:</strong> August 2017</p>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->SHIKHON-II<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '44-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-13 02:32:57', '2017-09-13 02:32:57', '', 44, 'http://share-education.org/44-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(941, 1, '2017-09-13 02:34:48', '2017-09-13 02:34:48', '<!--:en-->\r\n<h1>SHIKHON-II</h1>\r\n<strong>Location of activities:</strong> Bangladesh- 5 divisions, 17 districts and 58 Upazilas, 387 unions and 2582 villages of Bangladesh\r\n\r\n<strong>Project budget:</strong> 16,842,105 EURO\r\n\r\n<strong>EC contribution:</strong> 16,000,000\r\n\r\n<strong>Implementing agency:</strong> Save the Children – UK\r\n\r\n<strong>Co-financing / Local partner:</strong> Community Development Centre (CODEC); RDRS Bangladesh (RDRS); and Village Education Resource Centre (VERC)\r\n\r\n<strong>Starting date of implementation (contract signature date):</strong> 01 December 2011\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected end date:</strong> 30 November 2016 ( actual end date 28 February 2017)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Description:</h3>\r\n<strong>Overall Objective (s):</strong>\r\n\r\nTo contribute to the achievement of Bangladesh’s development goals, and to a national basic education framework.\r\n\r\n<strong>Project purpose:</strong>\r\n\r\nTo promote access and increase basic education outcomes for 160,400 hardest to reach and marginalized children while catalysing lessons-learning and other positive change in Bangladesh’ national education system\r\n\r\n<strong>Results:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected </strong><strong>Result 1</strong>: <strong>Access</strong>- Increased access to cost-effective non-formal basic education for 128,400 hardest to reach children in targeted communities.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 2</strong>: <strong>Quality</strong>- Increased efficiency and quality of non-formal basic education for 160,400 (128,400 non-formal+32,000 formal) children using holistic approaches for children to succeed in school.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 3</strong>:<strong> Linkages</strong>- Increased collaboration between the formal and non-formal primary education sectors to promote sharing and adoption of best practices.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Present Status:</h3>\r\n<strong>Activities:</strong>\r\n\r\nSHIKHON-II is the first among the 4 projects of SHARE education Programme to close in February 2017. All schools established by the project were closed in December 2016 as planned with students either completing their primary education cycle or mainstreamed into government primary schools (GPS).\r\n\r\nTo meet the expected result 1 relating to ‘Access’, SHIKHON-II established 4,290 schools in remote  coastal areas, chars and haors, and Chittagong Hill Tracts. Of this number 2,629 are Non-Formal Primary Education (NFPE) schools that offer readiness to grade 5 education and 1,661 Early Primary Education (EPE) schools that offer pre-primary to grade 2 education. SHIKHON-II enrolled 119,218 (69,181 NFPE &amp; 50,037 EPE) students including 569 adivasi/ethnic children through 30 Multi Lingual Education (MLE) centres in Chittagong Hill Tracts. The EPE students are mainstreamed to government primary schools (GPS) in the neighbouring areas at grade 3. A typical SHIKHON-II school is a community-provided, one-classroom school with one teacher who delivers education to a group of 30 to 35 children.\r\n\r\nIn total 68,439 students successfully passed the government’s primary education completion examination (PECE) and 47,872 pupils were mainstreamed into GPS at grade 3 having completed three-year education from pre-primary to grade 2 in SHIKHON-II schools.\r\n\r\nUnder the expected result 2 relating to ‘Quality’, the project ensured that the children acquire the necessary competencies at primary level. For this SHIKHON-II developed class-wise and subject-based teacher training courses and published class and subject specific teachers’ guides. SHIKHON-II teachers were trained in the SHIKHON accelerated curriculum, providing them with the experience and skills needed to help further their career. On average teachers received 3.4 month technical support visits by the teacher supervisor and technical officers. Parents and family members of SHIKHON students received parenting sessions on nutrition, early childhood development, and on how best they could support their children while they learn and develop. School Management Committees (SMCs) were established at every location and trained to oversee the operation of the school, as well as to develop and execute School Improvement Plans.\r\n\r\nTo address the expected result 3 relating to ‘Linkage’ SHIKHON-II developed  close relationship and networking with government agencies at central and field level. As a result all students of SHIKHON-II project schools received government support including clearence to operate schools, take the PECE exam, and free text books. The project established primary education change makers groups among GPS teachers who wanted to bring changesand improvements in their classroom teaching learning practices. The GPS teachers used phonetic charts of SHIKHON-II to upgrade  students’ pronunciation skills as well as teachers’ guidebooks produced by the project.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Lessons Learned:</strong>\r\n\r\nSHIKHON-II completed its operation in two phases: first phase saw the closure of about 50% of schools and downsizing the staff to almost half, the later phase saw the closure of all remaining schools and termination of all staff. Both operations were carried out in planned way with least or no social problem. In various regions project closing ceremonies were held to recount the achievements and benefits of the project and to thank the local community for their support. The closing ceremonies were participated by the local communities, government officials and head masters of neighbouring government schools. SHIKHON-II successfully leveraged its strong relations with government officials to disseminate information about SHIKHON-II’s achievements while advocating for changes in government schools to make education more accessible to the marginalized. The experience of SHIKHON-II including lessons learned is being documented by Save the Children International.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>Updated:</strong> August 2017</p>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->SHIKHON-II<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '44-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-13 02:34:48', '2017-09-13 02:34:48', '', 44, 'http://share-education.org/44-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
