(950, 1, '2017-09-13 03:12:34', '2017-09-13 03:12:34', '<h1><!--:en--><strong> </strong>UNIQUE (Unique intervention for quality primary education)-II</h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Location of activities:</strong>  Bangladesh- 26 districts, 84 upazila, 454 Unions and 1850 Villages\r\n\r\n<strong>Project budget:</strong> 16,472,143 EURO\r\n\r\n<strong>EC contribution:</strong> 15,575,981 EURO (95%)\r\n\r\n<strong>Implementing agency:</strong>  Dhaka Ahsania Mission (DAM)\r\n\r\n<strong>Co-financing / Local partner:</strong> Christian Commission for Development in Bangladesh (CCDB); Development Organisation of the Rural Poor (DORP); Padakhep Manabik Unnayan Kendra; SUROVI; Assistance for Social Organization and Development (ASOD); Voluntary Association for Rural Development (VARD); and Young Power in Social Action (YPSA\r\n\r\n<strong>Starting date of implementation (contract signature date):</strong> 30 November 2011\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected end date:</strong> 29 November 2017\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Overall Objectives:</strong>\r\n\r\nTo contribute to develop collaborative basic education system enabling all primary school-age children to avail quality education.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Project purpose:</strong>\r\n\r\nTo provide pre-primary and primary education to 297,467 disadvantaged children from the target geographically susceptible upazila and to develop institutional collaboration and horizontal learning mechanism between formal and non-formal primary education providers and to document and disseminate effective practices and lessons.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Results:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 1:</strong> Effectiveness of non-formal primary education programmes is increased in 26 project districts reaching the out of school children and catering their learning needs.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 2:</strong> Children’s performance is improved in formal schools of target 84 upazila.\r\n\r\n<strong>Expected Result 3:</strong> Child-centred learning community and supportive environment is developed in the target 454 unions of the project.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Present Status:</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Activities:</strong>\r\nUnder the expected result 1 the project provided pre-primary and primary education to 251,866 students (NFPE 197,043 and PPE 54,823, as of February 2017). For the first year UNIQUE-II continued to support 2,380 community-based children learning centres (CLC) established under EU funded UNIQUE-I project. At the end of first year these CLCs were transferred to local community with an enrolment of about 90,000 students. Subsequently 1850 new CLCs were established by UNIQUE-II on the basis of a baseline survey conducted in 2012. These 1,850 CLCs are reported to be in operation as of February 2017 with a total enrolment of 197,043 including about 600 adivasi children in CHT.\r\n\r\nUnder the expected result 2, a total of 1,200 learning camps were established in local government primary schools (GPS) where 28,666 low performing students of GPS received remedial academic support. For improving the quality of education, teachers and supervisors were given refresher courses. Subject based training on English and Maths were organized for teachers and supervisory staff. So far, 130 batches of subject based training were completed and a total of 2,173 teachers &amp; supervisors (1,930 female) received the training. Also, as part of foundation training, all teachers and supervisory staff of the project received training on PPE and remedial teaching camp. The NFPE teachers received pedagogic training on multi-grade teaching learning approach which is the major teaching approach developed by Dhaka Ahsania Mission. Students and teachers prepared learning materials with the locally available materials. Parents and the community participated in centre management committee (CMC) meetings in all CLCs. Joint meetings with parents and CMC members are held in every CLC for experience sharing and day to day management of the CLCs.\r\n\r\nUnder the expected result 3 UNIQUE-II engaged local government officials in various interventions. Union Parishad Standing Committees on Education (USCE) is a part of local government at union level that takes initiatives for improving education in respective unions. It also assists Union Parishad (UP) to make them more participatory and accountable for promoting quality education.  So far 3278 meetings of USCE were held and attended by respective representatives from the local government, LRC and CLCs members and UNIQUE-II project staff.  A learning Resource Centre (LRC) is established for exchange of experience, information and initiating collective actions to support quality education in the target villages. It is located in one of the CLC’s premises in every project union. 185 LRCs are now known to be functioning in the project areas. Parents and community are provided with livelihood linkage support through government’s safety net programme, micro-credit support programme, vocational skills training programme of different organizations. As part of family life education, Maa Literacy Campaign under this component titled “<em>Mayer Lekhapara </em>(Literacy for Mothers)” has facilitated literacy skills to 4,000 illiterate mothers by their own children who attend the CLCs. In addition, various national and international days are observed by the CLC community.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Lessons Learned:</strong>\r\n\r\nThe project contract states that 4,230 CLCs will run under the project in the hardest to reach locations of which 2,380 are those carried over from phase I of UNIQUE project and 1,850 newly established CLCs under UNIQUE II. At the end of 2012 or first year of the project, 2,380 CLCs were reported to have been handed over to the local community for their sustainability and management with an enrollment of 90,000 pupils. However as of December 2016 only 89 of the 2,380 CLCs are reported to be functioning, rest of the CLCs have gone out of existence. Therefore, it is also unlikely that the present 1,850 CLCs of UNIQUE-II will have a better survival rate if handed over to the local community after project closure in November 2017.\r\n\r\nAt the contract stage the project scope and targets were clearly ambitious if not inflated. It is noted that during implementation, the scope was changed in many ways and some peripheral activities were funded which may not have direct relation with children’s teaching and learning. On hind sight, it would have been more beneficial if the project had clear achievable targets of primary education completers and those mainstreamed to GPS.\r\n\r\nAn additional aspect of this project is the high overhead costs compared to three other projects. This together with the fact that only a smaller number of the NFPE students would have graduated at the end of the project makes the project rather uneconomic.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>Updated:</strong> August 2017</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div id=\"__if72ru4sdfsdfrkjahiuyi_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__zsc_once\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"__hggasdgjhsagd_once\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>\r\n<!--:-->', '<!--:en-->UNIQUE-II<!--:-->', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-13 03:12:34', '2017-09-13 03:12:34', '', 49, 'http://share-education.org/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
